<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="129" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="20.[189,311,1248,1274]" box="[189,311,1248,1274]" pageId="20" pageNumber="129">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,311,1248,1274]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="20" pageNumber="129" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,311,1248,1274]" pageId="20" pageNumber="129">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[189,1398,1295,1391]" pageId="20" pageNumber="129">
Vein R1 setulose. Male: scutellum without apical setae; pregonite with distal part curved and with a spine-like projection (
<figureCitation box="[450,560,1330,1356]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="21.[189,232,1892,1918]" captionTargetBox="[213,1374,297,1825]" captionTargetId="figure-11@21.[200,1387,265,1855]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="Fig. 11. Dexosarcophaga napo sp. nov., ♂, holotype (NHRS [lost]). A. Sternite 5, ventral view. B. Syntergosternite 7 +8, epandrium, cercus and surstylus, lateral view. C. Cerci, posterior view. D. Phallus and associated structures, lateral view. E. Distiphallus, ventral view. Abbreviations: see Material and methods. Scale bars =0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6823754" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6823754/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="129">Fig. 11D</figureCitation>
); vesica stick-like in lateral view, extremities enlarged in ventral view (
<figureCitation box="[199,341,1365,1391]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="21.[189,232,1892,1918]" captionTargetBox="[213,1374,297,1825]" captionTargetId="figure-11@21.[200,1387,265,1855]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="Fig. 11. Dexosarcophaga napo sp. nov., ♂, holotype (NHRS [lost]). A. Sternite 5, ventral view. B. Syntergosternite 7 +8, epandrium, cercus and surstylus, lateral view. C. Cerci, posterior view. D. Phallus and associated structures, lateral view. E. Distiphallus, ventral view. Abbreviations: see Material and methods. Scale bars =0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6823754" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6823754/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="129">Fig. 11D–E</figureCitation>
); juxta mostly membranous and almost squared (
<figureCitation box="[916,1006,1365,1391]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="17.[189,232,1822,1848]" captionTargetBox="[289,1298,265,1783]" captionTargetId="figure-11@17.[289,1298,265,1783]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="Fig. 8. Dexosarcophaga spp., ♂ and ♀, habitus and terminalia. A. Dexosarcophaga petra sp. nov., ♂, paratype (MNRJ [lost]), Brazil, Mato Grosso, Chapada dos Guimarães, terminalia, lateral view. B–D. Dexosarcophaga sphaera sp. nov., paratypes (MNRJ [lost]), Brazil, Brasília, Distrito Federal, Fazenda Vargem Bonita. B. ♂, habitus, lateral view. C. ♂, terminalia, lateral view. D. ♀, terminalia, ventral view. E–F. Dexosarcophaga napo sp. nov., ♂, paratype (NHRS [lost]), Ecuador, Napo Prov. E. Habitus, lateral view. F. Terminalia, lateral view. Scale bars =1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6823748" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6823748/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="129">Figs 8F</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1018,1071,1365,1391]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="21.[189,232,1892,1918]" captionTargetBox="[213,1374,297,1825]" captionTargetId="figure-11@21.[200,1387,265,1855]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="Fig. 11. Dexosarcophaga napo sp. nov., ♂, holotype (NHRS [lost]). A. Sternite 5, ventral view. B. Syntergosternite 7 +8, epandrium, cercus and surstylus, lateral view. C. Cerci, posterior view. D. Phallus and associated structures, lateral view. E. Distiphallus, ventral view. Abbreviations: see Material and methods. Scale bars =0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6823754" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6823754/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="129">11D</figureCitation>
). [Female unknown.]
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="129" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="20.[189,325,1431,1457]" box="[189,325,1431,1457]" pageId="20" pageNumber="129">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,325,1431,1457]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="20" pageNumber="129" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,325,1431,1457]" pageId="20" pageNumber="129">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[189,1399,1477,1539]" pageId="20" pageNumber="129">
The species epithet ‘ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Santos &amp; Pape &amp; Mello-Patiu" authorityYear="2022" box="[435,494,1478,1503]" class="Insecta" family="Sarcophagidae" genus="Dexosarcophaga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="129" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="napo">
<emphasis box="[435,494,1478,1503]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="129">napo</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’ should be treated as a noun in apposition. The name refers to the province (named after the Río 
<collectingRegion box="[438,503,1513,1539]" country="Ecuador" name="Napo" pageId="20" pageNumber="129">Napo</collectingRegion>
) of the 
<typeStatus box="[594,645,1513,1539]" pageId="20" pageNumber="129">type</typeStatus>
locality of the new species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
